So, what is synthetic biology? It depends on who you ask. According [ https=
://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFkc1uhSAQhZ_mstMgiMKCRTd9DcPPqLQKBsY2vn3xu=
mhC4OTMDCd8OIOwpHzpIxUk9zbhdYCO8Fs2QIRMzgJ5Cl53A5Nc9Ip4zZWl0g0klGnOALsJm8Z8=
AjlOuwVnMKT4HqGUCbJqxc3gh1EybhXvzNiZuXdMKik8owbGJ9icPkB0oOEH8pUiEJf2HSLeV5F=
Nr4hHefGPF_usK-yHcdiCSzHtoWBbm6t95PQFDssjawGaNDdVLhnK7dotLfdZrogrYHCNDal6V_=
VI0IwyRoeOd0yMjLa8dVX1koHqvRTKzK-e7kvju7actqBx33cwyTomtCmHuNSG79XssL0Llch0P=
-OMAa8JorEb-AcWPtDf-KYFIuT6GX4yWFELUWOpkGPfPXAqAqE6NSqhSE32qU7F_9A_R4GbaQ ]=
 to Christina Agapakis, it is =E2=80=9Cthe practice of engineering life.=E2=
=80=9D For one of the pioneers of the field named Drew Endy, synthetic biol=
ogy is focused on a meta-goal: to systematically improve our ability to use=
 biology as an engineering substrate.=C2=A0
Regardless of how you define it, the field of synthetic biology is comprise=
d of dreamers and doers. The vision expands as far as you can imagine: desi=
gning programmable cell therapies, learning how to grow rocket ships and sp=
ace stations, and bringing woolly mammoths back from extinction [ https://e=
mail.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFUEtuxCAMPc2wa8QnEFiw6KbXQAQ8GdQEInBa5fYlk0Uly=
7IlP79P8AhLqafdS0NyNYfnDjbDb1sBESo5GlSXomWKayFHQ6IVZqY6KJKae1aAzafVYj2A7Me8=
puAxlfyGUMoleVmuotRGGRVNDELJWZsYtZgYjRA8e97E_ogJcgALP1DPkoGEsm2Q8XpFVvtC3Nt=
DfD74V69Q1tKaX4d-1FeSLKecU8UE43LidBBD6NOoOZgxamn88zHSbfmIbGjH3NCH7wtLqs0F51=
JTXvrB98tv8H56mXGXgiMnPB1kP68Qb5945_V27hbIUHuO0XnsKUnZaanU08huX129NMxMRhrSm=
WPpqPxP-gcCOYIo ]. In practice, there is a relentless focus on discovering =
new molecular tools, scaling DNA synthesis, and creating systems of re-usab=
le standards and components. With the current rate of progress and the boun=
dless possibilities on the horizon, Eric Schmidt has said that =E2=80=9Cyou=
r industry is at the same stage mine was in 40 years ago when I started my =
career in tech.=E2=80=9D
How biotechs make money
So, synthetic biology is focused on learning how to build things using biol=
ogy. Before analyzing Ginkgo, it=E2=80=99s also important to think about ho=
w the biotech industry makes money. By and large, the revenue that flows th=
rough the ecosystem comes from selling drugs.
This seems like a simple statement, but it has non-obvious implications. Dr=
ugs are a very unique product. They require an enormous amount of R&D, and =
have to make it through many expensive hurdles to demonstrate efficacy and =
safety before being approved. After all of this time and cost there is anot=
her problem: the actual chemicals can be manufactured incredibly cheaply, w=
hich is why generic versions of drugs can be sold for as low as a dollar a =
day.
Companies are incentivized to develop new drugs by the promise of patent an=
d market exclusivity. Drug companies need to recoup all of their R&D and re=
gulatory costs in the time window of their exclusivity=E2=80=94and have als=
o found ways to extend the time that the window lasts.=C2=A0
With this incentive structure, biotech has become an industry with public c=
ompanies that have hundreds of employees and no product. The core value of =
these companies is the assets in their clinical pipeline=E2=80=94which stan=
d the chance to become blockbuster drugs with market exclusivity if they ar=
e approved. Approved assets are primarily sold to major pharmaceutical comp=
anies.
From a business strategy perspective, this has meant that most value captur=
e comes from pursuing highly specific vertical solutions=E2=80=94new drugs =
for specific diseases. Some of the most successful horizontal companies in =
the industry have focused on selling specific instruments or reagents to re=
search labs and companies. An example of this type of company is Illumina [=
 https://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFkEGOhCAQRU_T7MYAisKCxWzmGgSh2iaNYLA=
Y4-0H28UkhEBRn1_vO4uw5HLqLe9Irs3guYFOcOwREKGQukMxwWs2ctmLQRGvezVT6UYSdvMsAK=
sNUWOpQLY6x-Ashpw-Ekq5IC89sll6C0O7P8epn5y0CnoJwCyf5kncxrb6AMmBhl8oZ05AXF5XS=
Hh9RaJ-IW77o_9-8J-2juPoQox1Dcl2rbGVSNCcck5H1jMuJk67vnPtNEgOavBSKPt8DHRdvjzr=
9jrvaN370pKiU8Y5l5CW1vB-2RXi56EBmWuKmgKeBpKdI_ibFe_MPvRmgQSlZemNxZaUEM2WCjk=
N7GZrBEIxNSmhSHP2uanSv-kfLPGDoA ], which sells DNA sequencers and the reage=
nts necessary to generate new data. As biotech has matured, platform biotec=
hs [ https://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhCAQRb-m2WmKl8KCxWzmNwyPapu=
0gkGciX8_2C4mIeSmoOrUvd5WnHM5zZb3Sq5rqueGJuHvvmCtWMixY5liMHRgikuhSTBcO1B-IH=
GfngVxtXExtRxItsMt0dsac_q0ADBJXubJgldSqQGVcCNKJ-0AgwoWvLNe-BtsjxAxeTT4g-XMC=
YnP64qpXqPIYl61bvuDfz3Ydzshxz6XuSkKPQWurprgoxg7YNABUCU6TqJhwBgMlFMmRwY9731T=
QjHUIiip7fMhYJ27QPv9cHu1_t03Likm5epyiWluH94vu-LyeWgep2uxI8V6TpisWzDc9usd4ye=
QacaEpcUbJltbeFI2LEg1CnrbbaakpnrUUpNGDrl1pX_oH3QThjc ] have emerged that ar=
e aiming to change this dynamic by offering more expansive R&D infrastructu=
re that would have traditionally been built in-house by individual companie=
s.
We=E2=80=99ve all benefited enormously from platform biotechs. Moderna [ ht=
tps://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_T7Mbwq7Jg0Zu5hkEobdIKBspxvP=
1gu5iEVAhVrx7fcxZhTvk0WypIrjLguYGJcJQFECGTvUAegjes5b1QUhNvhB5p71oSyjBlgNWGx=
WDegWz7uARnMaT4kVDKFXmZUYOUneycl7QHPzEQamS2pYq3gk9wG9vdB4gODPxAPlME4tK6QsRr=
FVnMC3ErD_F88O96juNo1uQhR4u_TZ2sbyQYTjmnLROMq47TRjSu3mTPQUvfK22nh6Tr_OVZU_a=
xoHXvS0uyiQnHlEOc68D7ZVdYPo1KNFzf2GPAc4BoxwX8DYt3aB_8YYYIuYbpB4s1KqWqLVV9J9=
kNVxGUZrrTSpPq7FNVxX_TP8iBhBM ] isn=E2=80=99t a vaccine company, it is an m=
RNA therapeutics platform company. Before COVID, Moderna had created multip=
le internal portfolio companies that were pursuing specific vertical applic=
ations of their core technology. Because of the flexibility of their RNA te=
ch, they were able to design their COVID vaccine in a matter of hours after=
 receiving the DNA sequence of the virus. With the emergency vaccine approv=
al, we saw one of the fastest transitions from R&D to clinical administrati=
on in history.
Some platform companies focus on providing R&D services to biotechs instead=
 of launching their own internal companies like Moderna. Adimab [ https://e=
mail.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOhSAM_ZrLbgwgKCxYzGZ-w_CoXnIVDNYx_v2gLiZpm=
qbt6ek53iJMuZxmzRuSKw14rmASHNsMiFDIvkEZYjCs46qVQpNgWu2o8h2J2zAWgMXG2WDZgay7=
m6O3GHO6IZRySd5GQT-yvrMQgpAjF8o55kZqPW2FoqN_iO0eIiQPBn6hnDkB8XlZIOF1iszmjbh=
ur_b7xX9qHMfR2BAX65q6VhskGk45px1rGZc9p03b-FoJxUGLoKS240vQZfoKrNl2t6H1nwtLik=
kZXS4xTXXh87YLzPegyhmuH_YU8RwgWTdDeJTi49itfZggQalOhsFi9UnKSkul6gV7lNX_pWa61=
1KTyhxyRaV_0j91B4Mq ], for example, partners with biotechs and pharma compa=
nies to help them make antibody therapies so that they don=E2=80=99t have t=
o do it themselves. As one of the Adimab co-founders Tillman Gerngross put =
it, =E2=80=9CAirlines don=E2=80=99t build their own airplanes, and there=E2=
=80=99s a good reason for that. They focus on the particular thing they=E2=
=80=99re good at and leave other parts to others. And I think our industry =
is maturing in a similar way.=E2=80=9D This evolution will be essential for=
 understanding Ginkgo.
What does The Organism Company do?
While biotech was heavily focused on making drugs, synthetic biologists con=
tinued to spend their time developing better ways to engineer organisms. Ma=
ny of the founders of the discipline entered into the world of biology from=
 computer science, electrical engineering, and other fields with a deep emp=
hasis on general solutions and explicit standards.
These early leaders were deeply optimistic about the technological progress=
 being made in both DNA sequencing [ https://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJx=
VkM2OhCAQhJ9muGkQhZEDh73saxh-WoesggvtTnz77RkPm02AkFR1FXzeIiy5nGbPFdnrmPDcwS=
R41hUQobCjQpliMJ0SYy8HzYLpteOjVyzWaS4Am42rwXIA2w-3Rm8x5vQe4VxI9jBqDNrNflYqz=
FqNUigXHAfbd947qdxVbI8QIXkw8APlzAmYz9sGCV9RbDUPxL3e-o-b-KTlSTjINruY23q4itZ_=
tTRB2k77-bBYmxDnGQpZm90WbCi0qfB9UE1MC4tGcCG46vpOyLvgbd96ug2jAD2EUWo73wa-LU3=
o_lWwYlJGlwuFkOHrYTdY3wIBmF6vPlLEc4Jk3QrhYoMX4zetaYEEhdiHySKRlZJquRzvQ3exoB=
9L3em7lppRc8g0lf5KfwGXoJbr ] and synthesis [ https://email.mg-d1.substack.c=
om/c/eJxVkcuOhCAQRb-m2WkQxceCxSST_g3Do1TSCgbKMf79VLeLySQUIbm36sLBaoQ5pkvtMS=
N7byNeO6gAZ14BERI7MqTRO1W1oq9lMzCn6sHw3rbM53FKAJv2q8J0ANsPs3qr0cfwaeFcSLao2=
kno2l4Dr_oatKvkJKZWO-gmYzor72B9OA_BgoIfSFcMwGzcNgj4HsVWtSDu-VF_PcSTliXhINtk=
fCzzYTJq-yqpg7Sd6lw05sL5aYJE1mLXCQs8Y5GvgAtkT6OeVN8n80pwIXhb1ZWQneBlXVo6Nb2=
AoXG9HPT0aPg2F676l8SSChFNTD7MZHgteoP1IxCH8X35I3i8RgjarOBuRHij_kAbZwiQ6AvcqJ=
EAS0mxXPZdU91I6OFyqIZukAOjZBepK_yF_gJxbZjY ] that provided the essential to=
oling to manipulate and engineer organisms. Engineers like Tom Knight and D=
rew Endy at MIT talked about what was necessary to take genetic engineering=
 to the next level. In order to operate like other engineering disciplines,=
 the field needed several new concepts.
First, builders needed standardized parts with predictable behavior that th=
ey could compose and assemble in new ways. There also needed to be meaningf=
ul abstraction layers=E2=80=94analogies were often made to modern programmi=
ng languages that let programmers focus on logic instead of machine code. W=
e needed to move from worrying about raw bases of DNA=E2=80=94ATTCGGATA=E2=
=80=94to programs closer to the lac operon. Another core emphasis was to mo=
re effectively coordinate labor=E2=80=94separating designers of genetic pro=
grams from the builders directly compiling it.
In other words, biology needed to develop the necessary infrastructure to b=
ecome a true engineering discipline.
The iGEM competition has been one of the most vibrant communities for makin=
g progress on these foundational goals. The teams can spend their time focu=
sing on their most ambitious ideas because they are building using a shared=
 Parts Registry, a Distribution Kit, and a set of Assembly Standards. Inste=
ad of worrying about the behavior of every single enzyme in a new circuit, =
they can take enzymes off the shelf and spend their effort brainstorming ho=
w best to program molds [ https://email.mg-d1.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uwyAQhU=
8TdrUAgw0LFpWiniBdW_xMHBQDFh638u1L4kUlNALNG755z1uEudTDrGVD8ioTHiuYDL_bAohQy=
b5BnWIwbOCql0KTYHrtqPIDidt0rwDJxsVg3YGsu1uitxhLfo9QyiV5mMEJqnp2F-CtujvpuAyO=
eSUFG-2o1Am2e4iQPRj4gXqUDMSXlCDj6yuymAfiul36zwv_aodTTrs4Q-pKndv7Bja15vX2_XG=
FnGx9kmiaiNOB9YzLscn7zrebUBy0CEpqe78ImuaPwLptdxta_-wak1STC7pSY56b4PmwCZZ3o_=
mbXkvtOeIxQbZugXBaxzPCdxjTDBlqizZMFltwUjYslWoU7LTaDEnN9KilJo0cSpvK_9A_822HS=
g ] into assembly lines producing foods, detergents, and medicines. This et=
hos is reflected in the beautifully nerdy fact that the iGEM grand prize is=
 the BioBrick Trophy: a giant aluminum brick that looks like a Lego block.
Even as synthetic biology and iGEM gained traction, some of the leading pro=
fessors like Tom Knight still struggled to get their work funded. The work =
didn=E2=80=99t neatly align with the core priorities of any major grant age=
ncies and was very early. At one point, an MIT grad student named Jason Kel=
ly asked Tom, =E2=80=9CWhat do you think if we started a company?=E2=80=9D =
Tom responded, =E2=80=9CWhat would you think if I joined you?=E2=80=9D Whil=
e most professors were happy to =E2=80=9Cspin out=E2=80=9D companies from t=
heir labs, Tom Knight wanted to dive in and join the adventure.
